  { q: 'Does PDF cropping permanently remove content?', a: 'No. PDF cropping works by setting a CropBox — a property that tells PDF viewers to display only a portion of each page. The content outside the crop area is hidden, not deleted. The original full-size content is still inside the file and can be uncropped at any time.' },
  { q: 'Will all pages be cropped the same way?', a: 'Yes — the PDFWonder crop tool applies the same margin amounts to all pages. For cropping individual pages differently, extract them first with the PDF Splitter, crop each separately, then merge them back.' },
  { q: 'What unit does the tool use?', a: 'Millimetres (mm). The tool converts internally to PDF points (1 mm = 2.835 points).' },
  { q: 'Why does my cropped PDF still show the full page in some viewers?', a: 'Some PDF viewers (especially older ones) ignore the CropBox and display the full MediaBox instead. Most modern viewers (Adobe Reader, Chrome, Edge, Preview on Mac) respect the CropBox correctly.' },
  { q: 'Can I crop a scanned PDF to remove black borders?', a: 'Yes. Scanner black borders are part of the visual content, but cropping via CropBox will hide them from view. This is the most common use case for PDF cropping.' },
  { q: 'Is my PDF uploaded when I use PDFWonder?', a: 'No. All processing happens in your browser using pdf-lib. Your files never leave your device.' },
];
