<h2>How PDF Cropping Works (CropBox vs. MediaBox)</h2>

<p>
  PDF pages have two invisible rectangles that control what is visible:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>MediaBox:</strong> The full physical size of the page, including all content. This is the actual page dimensions.</li>
  <li><strong>CropBox:</strong> The visible window — what PDF viewers display. Setting a CropBox smaller than the MediaBox "hides" the content outside the crop area.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  PDF cropping tools like PDFWonder set the CropBox, not the MediaBox. This means the hidden content is still technically in the file — it is just masked from view. This is why PDF cropping is non-destructive and reversible.
</p>

<h2>How to Crop a PDF in Adobe Acrobat</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Adobe Acrobat (Pro required for editing).</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Tools → Edit PDF → Crop Pages</strong>.</li>
  <li>Draw a selection rectangle on the page to define the crop area.</li>
  <li>Double-click inside the selection to open the "Set Page Boxes" dialog.</li>
  <li>Set the CropBox margins, then choose to apply to all pages or a range.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>OK</strong> and save the file.</li>
</ol>

<h2>How to Crop a PDF on Mac (Preview)</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Preview.</li>
  <li>Use the selection tool (the dotted rectangle icon) to draw a crop rectangle on a page.</li>
  <li>Go to <strong>Tools → Crop</strong> (or press Command+K).</li>
  <li>Note: Preview's crop permanently alters the MediaBox, not just the CropBox — this is a destructive crop unlike the PDFWonder approach.</li>
  <li>Save the file. The content outside the crop area is permanently removed.</li>
</ol>

<h2>How to Crop a PDF in Google Chrome (Print Method)</h2>

<p>Chrome has a limited workaround:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Chrome.</li>
  <li>Press <strong>Ctrl+P</strong> to print.</li>
  <li>In the print dialog, set a custom "Scale" and adjust margins to achieve a rough crop.</li>
  <li>Print to PDF (choose "Save as PDF" as the printer).</li>
</ol>
<p>This method is imprecise and does not support exact mm-level cropping — use the browser tool above for precise control.</p>

<h2>Common Reasons to Crop a PDF</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Scanner black borders:</strong> Remove the dark border that appears around scanned pages</li>
  <li><strong>Oversized margins:</strong> Academic papers and reports often have very wide margins — crop them for e-reader display</li>
  <li><strong>Removing headers/footers:</strong> Strip existing headers or footers before adding new ones</li>
  <li><strong>Fitting a smaller screen:</strong> Crop down to just the content area for better readability on phones and tablets</li>
  <li><strong>Booklet printing:</strong> Crop to a specific paper size before sending to print</li>
</ul>

